{"title_page": "The Wakefield Daily Item", "text_new": "{{Infobox Newspaper\n| name                = The Wakefield Boring Daily Item\n| logo                = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| type                = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| foundation          = May 7, 1894\n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = [[USD]] .50 daily\n| owners              = The Wakefield Item Co.\n| publisher           = Glenn D. Dolbeare\n| editor              = Robert Burgess\n| language            = \n| political           = \n| circulation         = approximately 4,800 daily<ref>[http://www.mondotimes.com/1/world/us/21/1121/15404 Wakefield Daily Item \u2013 daily newspaper in Wakefield, Massachusetts USA with local news and events], accessed March 26, 2012.</ref>\n| headquarters        = 26 Albion Street, [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]] 01880 United States\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = [http://www.wakefielditem.com/ wakefielditem.com]\n}}\n\n'''''The Wakefield Daily Item''''' is an independent weekday [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]], with issues published Mondays through Fridays.\n\nFred W. Young printed the first ''Item'' on May 7, 1894, running the paper until selling to printer Alstead W. Browne in March 1900; he sold out to Harris M. Dolbeare, who established the Wakefield Item Company April 1, 1900.<ref name=\"about\">[http://www.wakefielditem.com/about.htm WakefieldItem.com: About], accessed January 26, 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103153635/http://www.wakefielditem.com/about.htm |date=January 3, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe Item is famous for the \"Looking Backward\" column, detailing events that took place in Wakefield and around the country 25, 50, 75, and 100 years ago from the date of the newspaper.\n\nThe Item's presidents have all been Dolbeare's heirs\u2014his widow Emma Dolbeare, sons Cyrus and Richard Dolbeare, and now grandson Glenn Dolbeare. The paper has had seven editors: Harris Dolbeare (1900\u2013his death in 1938), Gardner Campbell (1938\u20131953), Robert C. Reed (1953\u20131966), Kendall Dolbeare (1966\u20131986), Janet Constantakes (1986\u20131988) and Peter Rossi (since 1988).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe newspaper competes for readers in Wakefield with a local edition of the ''[[Daily Times Chronicle]]'', based in nearby [[Woburn, Massachusetts|Woburn]] and [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]]; and with the ''Wakefield Observer'', a [[weekly newspaper]] published at the [[Beverly, Massachusetts|Beverly]] office of [[Community Newspaper Company]].\n\nOn January 27, 2009, the Item changed its format from [[broadsheet]] to [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]].\n\nThe Item is located at [[Item Building|26 Albion Street]] in the [[Common District (Wakefield, Massachusetts)|town center]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Item Building|Item Building (Wakefield, Massachusetts)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wakefielditem.com ''The Wakefield Daily Item'' Website]\n\n{{WakefieldMA}}\n{{Newspapers in Massachusetts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wakefield Daily Item}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n\n{{Massachusetts-newspaper-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox Newspaper\n| name                = The Wakefield Daily Item\n| logo                = \n| image               = \n| caption             = \n| type                = [[Daily newspaper]]\n| format              = [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|Tabloid]]\n| foundation          = May 7, 1894\n| ceased publication  = \n| price               = [[USD]] .50 daily\n| owners              = The Wakefield Item Co.\n| publisher           = Glenn D. Dolbeare\n| editor              = Robert Burgess\n| language            = \n| political           = \n| circulation         = approximately 4,800 daily<ref>[http://www.mondotimes.com/1/world/us/21/1121/15404 Wakefield Daily Item \u2013 daily newspaper in Wakefield, Massachusetts USA with local news and events], accessed March 26, 2012.</ref>\n| headquarters        = 26 Albion Street, [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]] 01880 United States\n| ISSN                = \n| website             = [http://www.wakefielditem.com/ wakefielditem.com]\n}}\n\n'''''The Wakefield Daily Item''''' is an independent weekday [[daily newspaper]] published in [[Wakefield, Massachusetts]], with issues published Mondays through Fridays.\n\nFred W. Young printed the first ''Item'' on May 7, 1894, running the paper until selling to printer Alstead W. Browne in March 1900; he sold out to Harris M. Dolbeare, who established the Wakefield Item Company April 1, 1900.<ref name=\"about\">[http://www.wakefielditem.com/about.htm WakefieldItem.com: About], accessed January 26, 2007.  {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070103153635/http://www.wakefielditem.com/about.htm |date=January 3, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe Item is famous for the \"Looking Backward\" column, detailing events that took place in Wakefield and around the country 25, 50, 75, and 100 years ago from the date of the newspaper.\n\nThe Item's presidents have all been Dolbeare's heirs\u2014his widow Emma Dolbeare, sons Cyrus and Richard Dolbeare, and now grandson Glenn Dolbeare. The paper has had seven editors: Harris Dolbeare (1900\u2013his death in 1938), Gardner Campbell (1938\u20131953), Robert C. Reed (1953\u20131966), Kendall Dolbeare (1966\u20131986), Janet Constantakes (1986\u20131988) and Peter Rossi (since 1988).<ref name=\"about\"/>\n\nThe newspaper competes for readers in Wakefield with a local edition of the ''[[Daily Times Chronicle]]'', based in nearby [[Woburn, Massachusetts|Woburn]] and [[Reading, Massachusetts|Reading]]; and with the ''Wakefield Observer'', a [[weekly newspaper]] published at the [[Beverly, Massachusetts|Beverly]] office of [[Community Newspaper Company]].\n\nOn January 27, 2009, the Item changed its format from [[broadsheet]] to [[Tabloid (newspaper format)|tabloid]].\n\nThe Item is located at [[Item Building|26 Albion Street]] in the [[Common District (Wakefield, Massachusetts)|town center]].\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Item Building|Item Building (Wakefield, Massachusetts)]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.wakefielditem.com ''The Wakefield Daily Item'' Website]\n\n{{WakefieldMA}}\n{{Newspapers in Massachusetts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wakefield Daily Item}}\n[[Category:Newspapers published in Massachusetts]]\n[[Category:Media in Middlesex County, Massachusetts]]\n\n{{Massachusetts-newspaper-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2601:19c:4704:c80:59f3:3a2e:a02c:3a8b", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Wakefield_Daily_Item"}
{"title_page": "Satoru K\u014dsaki", "text_new": "{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Satoru K\u014dsaki\n| image            = \n| caption          = \n| image_size       = <!-- Only for images narrower than 220 pixels -->\n| background       = non_performing_personnel\n| native_name      = \u795e\u524d \u6681\n| native_name_lang = ja\n| alias            = Shinji Ikeda\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|1974|9|16}}\n| birth_place      = [[Toyonaka, Osaka]], Japan\n| genre            = {{flatlist|\n* [[J-pop]]\n* [[anison]] \n* [[synthpop]] \n* [[nu jazz]]\n* [[techno]]\n* [[classical music|classical]]\n* [[video game music]]\n}}\n| occupation       = {{flatlist|\n* Composer\n* arranger\n* producer\n* musician\n}}\n| instrument       = [[Trumpet]]\n| years_active     = 1999&ndash;present\n| associated_acts  = {{flatlist|\n*[[Keiichi Okabe]]\n*[[Hidekazu Tanaka]]\n*Ryuichi Takada\n*Hiroshi Okubo\n}}\n}}\n{{Nihongo|'''Satoru K\u014dsaki'''|\u795e\u524d \u6681|K\u014dsaki Satoru|born September 16, 1974}} is a Japanese [[composer]] and [[arranger]] best known for his work on [[anime]] series, including ''[[Lucky Star (manga)|Lucky Star]]'', ''[[The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya]]'', ''[[Monogatari (series)|Monogatari]]'', and ''[[Beastars]]''. In 1998, he began his career at [[Namco]], primarily composing music for video games. Since 2005, he has been affiliated with [[Keiichi Okabe]]'s music production company Monaca, where he has often collaborated with his colleagues to produce soundtracks for anime and other media.\n\n== Biography ==\nK\u014dsaki was born on September 16, 1974 in [[Toyonaka, Osaka]], Japan.<ref>{{cite web |title=\u30b9\u30bf\u30c3\u30d5 |url=https://www.senpai.info/staff/ |website=\u79c1\u306e\u512a\u3057\u304f\u306a\u3044\u5148\u8f29 |accessdate=16 February 2020| trans-title = Staff| trans-website = Watashi no Yasashikunai Senpai|language=ja}}</ref> He began playing the piano and [[Electone]] when he was about three years old, and played the trumpet in his junior high school's brass band.<ref name = \"steinberg\">{{cite web |title=\u795e\u524d\u6681 |url=https://japan.steinberg.net/jp/artists/steinberg_stories/satoru_kosaki.html |website=Steinberg |accessdate=16 February 2020|trans-title=Satoru K\u014dsaki|language=ja}}</ref> As an information engineering student at [[Kyoto University]], he learned to compose music as a member of the amateur circle {{Nihongo|\"Yoshida Music Factory\"|\u5409\u7530\u97f3\u697d\u88fd\u4f5c\u6240|Yoshida Ongaku Seisakusho}}.<ref name=\"steinberg\" />\n\nAfter his graduation in 1999, he was hired at [[Namco]], where he composed tracks for video game series including ''[[Tekken]]'' and ''[[Kotoba no Puzzle: Mojipittan|Kotoba no Puzzle]]''.<ref name=\"steinberg\" /> During his time at Namco he was also part of Hiroshi Okubo's doujin circle nanosounds, where he contributed original tracks to a number of albums.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://homepage3.nifty.com/hirokubo/disc.htm|title=nanosounds official website|last=|first=|date=|website=nanosounds|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20050115084628fw_/http://homepage3.nifty.com/hirokubo/disc.htm|archive-date=January 15, 2005|access-date=February 17, 2020|language=ja}}</ref> He would also score the music for the OVA ''[[Munto|Munto 2: Beyond the Walls of Time]]'' using the alias Shinji Ikeda, as he was still employed at Namco at the time.<ref name=\"JASRAC\">{{Cite web |title=\u300c\u97f3\u4eba\u5de5\u623f\u300d\u3000\u795e\u524d \u6681 |url=https://www.jasrac.or.jp/otobito/interview06/ |accessdate=25 February 2020|language=ja}}</ref> Citing a desire to compose a greater variety of music, he left the company in 2005 to join Monaca, a production group founded by his former colleague [[Keiichi Okabe]].<ref>{{cite web |title=\u30a2\u30cb\u30e1\u306b\u6b20\u304b\u305b\u306a\u3044\u30b5\u30a6\u30f3\u30c9\u3092\u624b\u639b\u3051\u308bMONACA\u306b\u805e\u304f\u3001\u6c17\u92ed\u306e\u30b5\u30a6\u30f3\u30c9\u30af\u30ea\u30a8\u30a4\u30bf\u30fc\u96c6\u56e3\u306e\u904e\u53bb\u304b\u3089\u73fe\u5728\u307e\u3067\u3010MONACA\u30a4\u30f3\u30bf\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc\u524d\u7de8\u3011 |url=https://webnewtype.com/report/article/76494/ |website=[[Newtype|WebNewtype]] |accessdate=16 February 2020|language=ja}}</ref> \n\nK\u014dsaki's first major project with Monaca was the soundtrack for the 2006 anime television series ''[[The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya]]''; [[List_of_Haruhi_Suzumiya_albums#Suzumiya_Haruhi_no_Tsumeawase|an album]] containing three of his compositions (\"God knows...\", \"Lost my music\", and \"Koi no Mikuru Densetsu\") sold more than 136,000 copies in Japan and peaked at #5 on the weekly [[Oricon Singles Chart]].<ref name=\"ANN\">{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2008-07-17/haruhi-cd-stays-on-japanese-singles-chart-for-100th-week| title=''Haruhi'' CD Stays on Japanese Singles Chart for 100th Week|publisher=[[Anime News Network]]|date=2008-07-18|accessdate =2008-07-18}}</ref> In 2007, he composed the soundtrack for the anime television series ''[[Lucky Star (manga)|Lucky Star]]''; the series' opening theme \"[[List_of_Lucky_Star_albums#Motteke!_Sailor_Fuku|Motekke! Sailor Fuku]]\" peaked at #2 upon release.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2007-06-27/lucky-star-special-edition |title=Lucky Star Special Edition DVD Flies off Shelves in Akiba |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |date=June 27, 2007 |accessdate=2007-06-27}}</ref> It would also go on to win the Radio Kansai Award, a subset of the [[Animation Kobe#Animation Kobe Theme Song Award|Animation Kobe Theme Song Award]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Ghibli's Takahata, Paprika, Geass Win Anime Kobe Awards |publisher=[[Anime News Network]] |date=2007-09-27 |url=http://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2007-09-27/ghibli%27s-takahata-paprika-geass-win-anime-kobe-awards |accessdate=2009-04-18}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2010, K\u014dsaki announced an indefinite hiatus from his work due to poor health.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Loo |first1=Egan |title=Haruhi Composer Satoru Kousaki on Hiatus Due to Health |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2010-12-08/haruhi-composer-satoru-kousaki-on-hiatus-due-to-health |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |date=7 December 2010}}</ref> He began a second illness-related hiatus in February 2014<ref>{{cite web |title=Monaca Composer Satoru Kousaki Goes on Hiatus Due to Health |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2014-02-24/monaca-composer-satoru-kousaki-goes-on-hiatus-due-to-health |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=24 February 2020 |date=24 February 2014}}</ref> and returned to work in January 2015.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Nelkin |first1=Sarah |title=Monaca Composer Satoru Kousaki Recovers From Illness, Returns to Work |url=https://www.animenewsnetwork.com/news/2015-01-01/monaca-composer-satoru-kousaki-recovers-from-illness-returns-to-work/.82808 |website=[[Anime News Network]] |accessdate=16 February 2020 |date=1 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, he worked on the anime ''[[Beastars]]'', which features [[Romani music|gypsy]]-inspired music.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Lehecka |first1=Eddie |title=Interview With BEASTARS Composer Satoru Kosaki: Music Inspiring Instinct |url=https://www.otaquest.com/interview-beastars-composer-satoru-kosaki/ |website=OTAQUEST |accessdate=25 February 2020 |date=11 February 2020}}</ref> In 2020 a compilation album titled ''Satoru Kosaki 20th Anniversary Selected Works \"DAWN\"'' was released to commemorate 20 years of being a composer. It includes a selection of his most successful songs, while the limited edition release also includes a selection of anime BGM.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dennison |first=Kara |title=Haruhi and Monogatari Composer Releases 20th Anniversary Collection |url=https://www.crunchyroll.com/en-gb/anime-news/2019/11/29/haruhi-and-monogatari-composer-releases-20th-anniversary-collection |website=[[Crunchyroll]] |accessdate=25 February 2020 |date=29 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=\u795e\u524d\u6681 \u4f5c\u66f2\u5bb6\u30c7\u30d3\u30e5\u30fc20\u5468\u5e74\u8a18\u5ff5CD\u300c\u795e\u524d \u6681 20th Anniversary Selected Works \u201cDAWN\u201d\u300d |url=https://kosakisatoru-20th-anniversary.com/ |website=Satoru Kosaki 20th Anniversary Selected Works \"DAWN\"}}</ref>\n\n== Works ==\n=== Anime ===\n{{legend2|#bbffbb|Background music composition|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{{legend2|#F9F9F9|Other credits only (e.g. opening/ending themes)|border=1px solid #AAAAAA}}\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Year\n! Title<ref name=\"monaca\">{{cite web |title=WORKS - \u795e\u524d \u6681 |url=http://www.monaca.jp/archive/kosaki.html |website=MONACA |accessdate=February 13, 2020|language=ja}}</ref>\n! class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2005\n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Munto|Munto 2: Beyond the Walls of Time]]''\n| & theme song \"Toki no Kabe o Koete\", lyrics; as Shinji Ikeda\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2006 \n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Haruhi Suzumiya|The Melancholy of Haruhi Suzumiya]]''\n| & insert songs \"God knows...\", \"Lost my music\", and \"Koi no Mikuru Densetsu\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"1\" | 2007\n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Lucky Star (manga)|Lucky Star]]''\n| & opening theme \"Motteke! Sailor Fuku\", various insert songs\n|-\n! rowspan=\"4\" | 2008\n| ''[[Penguin Musume|Penguin Musume Heart]]''\n| opening theme \"Ren'ai Jiy\u016b Shoujo\"\n|-\n| ''[[Sekirei]]''\n| opening theme \"Sekirei\", ending theme \"Dear sweet heart\"\n|-\n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Lucky Star (manga)|Lucky Star OVA]]''\n|\n|-\n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Kannagi (manga)|Kannagi: Crazy Shrine Maidens]]''\n| & opening theme \"Motto Hade ni ne!\", ending themes \"Musuhi no Toki\" and \"Shirigeya no Theme\", various insert songs\n|-\n! rowspan=\"6\" | 2009\n| style=\"background:#bbffbb;\" | ''[[Munto|Sora o Miageru Sh\u014djo no Hitomi ni Utsuru Sekai]]''\n| & insert s