akunare, Gunjo'' {{small|<nowiki>[</nowiki>[[:ja:\u3044\u306a\u304f\u306a\u308c\u3001\u7fa4\u9752#\u6620\u753b|ja]]<nowiki>]</nowiki>}}\n| live-action film; with Kuniyuki Takahashi\n|-\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.monaca.jp/member/ Profile] at Monaca {{in lang|ja}}\n* [https://vgmdb.net/artist/126 Discography at VGMdb]\n* {{ann|people|55249}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kosaki, Satoru}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century male musicians]]\n[[Category:Anime composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese male composers]]\n[[Category:Japanese music arrangers]]\n[[Category:Japanese television composers]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Male film score composers]]\n[[Category:Male television composers]]\n[[Category:Musicians from Osaka]]\n[[Category:People from Toyonaka, Osaka]]\n[[Category:Video game composers]]\n", "name_user": "Goszei", "label": "safe", "comment": "lead rewrite #2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Satoru_K%C5%8Dsaki"}
{"title_page": "Maira Kalman", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Maira Kalman\n| image = Maira kalman 2010.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Kalman at the 2010 [[Texas Book Festival]]\n| birth_name = <!--if different-->\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1949}}\n| birth_place = [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]]\n| nationality = American\n| known_for = [[Illustrator]], [[writer]]\n| education = New York University\n| movement = \n| spouse = Tibor Kalman (m. 1981, d. 1999)\n| notable_works = \n| patrons = \n| awards = \n| website = {{URL | mairakalman.com | MairaKalman.com }}\n}}\n\n'''Maira Kalman''' ({{lang-he|\u05de\u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d4 \u05e7\u05dc\u05de\u05df}}; born 1949) is an [[Israel]]i-born American illustrator, writer, artist, and designer. She is known for her playful and witty illustrations, featured in publications such as ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The New Yorker]]'', and the children's books that she has both written and illustrated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fromthegrapevine.com/arts/maira-kalman-new-yorker-artist|title=Maira Kalman is more than just a quirky cartoonist for The New Yorker|website=From the Grapevine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/04/profile-maira-kalman-author-and-illustrator.html|title=The Singular Magic of Maira Kalman|last=Alam|first=Rumaan|date=2018-04-30|website=The Cut|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The urban environment of [[New York City]] brings Kalman's creativity to life. She has collaborated with New York institutions, such as [[The Museum of Modern Art]]. She has also drawn inspiration from the city's geography and well known landmarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman|title=\"Something Essential\": A Q&A with Maira Kalman|date=2014-07-01|website=Guggenheim|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Her [[picture book]], ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of the John J. Harvey'', can be found in [[WorldCat]] library. This book was both written and illustrated by Kalman. It won the annual [[Boston Globe\u2013Horn Book Award]] for Nonfiction in 2003.<ref>[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n86-012344/ \"Kalman, Maira\"]. [[WorldCat]]. Retrieved 2014-10-02.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKalman was born in [[Tel Aviv]], Israel. Her parents had emigrated to Israel in the 1930s, and her father was a fervent [[Zionism|Zionist]] who was a member of [[Irgun]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/the-pursuits-of-maira-kalman/|title=The Pursuits of Maira Kalman|last=Herschthal|first=Eric|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> Her mother, Sara Berman, was originally from [[Belarus]] and had moved to Israel to escape [[Pogrom|pogroms]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Green|first=Penelope|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/03/arts/design/inside-sara-bermans-closet-at-the-met-museum.html|title=Inside Sara Berman's Closet at the Met Museum|date=2017-03-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> When Kalman was growing up in Israel, the women in her family \"...worked like beasts from morning to night. It was that sense of dedicating yourself to a life of taking care of the people you love, by baking and sewing and cleaning,\" Kalman explained.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWhen Kalman was four years old, her family moved to [[New York City]], so that her father could expand his diamond business.<ref>{{cite web |title=Julie Saul Projects |url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/highlight/maira-kalman/the-autobiography-of-alice-b-toklas}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> The family lived in [[Riverdale, Bronx]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman|title=\"Something Essential\": A Q&A with Maira Kalman|date=2014-07-01|website=Guggenheim|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Her mother, Sara, spent a significant amount of time at the [[Loehmann's]] department store.<ref name=\":5\" /> She was known for her chic style, and she wore only white. Kalman attended the [[High School of Music & Art]], now known as [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|LaGuardia High School]], where she studied art and received a Bachelors of Arts degree.<ref>[http://illustrationfriday.com/blog/2008/09/28/master-of-the-month-maira-kalman/ Master of the Month: Maira Kalman] from ''IllustrationFriday.com''</ref> She attended [[New York University]] where she studied English literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saulgallery.com/kalman/biography.html|title=Julie Saul Gallery|date=2007-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212083136/http://www.saulgallery.com/kalman/biography.html|access-date=2019-04-02|archive-date=December 12, 2007}}</ref> By the time Kalman had left for college, her parents had returned to Israel.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAt the age of 18, Kalman met designer [[Tibor Kalman]], a native of [[Budapest]] who had moved to New York City as a child, at New York University.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/people/18048717/|title=M&Co {{!}} People {{!}} Collection of Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|website=collection.cooperhewitt.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> She explained, \"We met in this class of misfits in summer school. They said, {{em|You have to take these classes, otherwise we're going to throw you out.}} What was interesting was the mix of crazy people in that group... So we met there, and he asked me out on a date. And you know in your life, when you meet somebody [and] you go, 'I've known you for a thousand years,' and there's not even an iota of a question?\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1979, Maira and Tibor founded the graphic and design consultancy, [[M & Co. (design firm)|M & Co.]] The firm grew to be highly influential; it was known for its innovative use of images and typography.<ref name=\":3\" /> M & Co. created work for ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine, Restaurant Florent, the band [[Talking Heads]], the [[National Audubon Society]], and the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.aiga.org/aiga/content/inspiration/aiga-medalist/2016-aiga-medalist-maira-kalman/|title=2016 AIGA Medalist Maira Kalman|work=AIGA {{!}} the professional association for design|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nKalman played a critical role in the development of M & Co, but her priorities began to shift with the birth of her children, Lulu (1983) and Alex (1985).<ref name=\":2\" /> Beginning in the mid-1980s, Kalman began to publish children's book. Her first children's book, ''Stay Up Late'' (1985), featured illustrations paired lyrics of musician [[David Byrne]]. The book told the story of children who prevent their baby brother from falling asleep.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-670-81895-2|title=Stay Up Late|website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990s, Tibor served as the [[editor-in-chief]] of [[Colors (magazine)|''COLORS'' magazine]]. The magazine was known for confronting topics such as [[ecology]] and [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Porter|first=By Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/may/07/guardianobituaries.markporter|title=Tibor Kalman|date=1999-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 1999, Tibor passed away. Maira Kalman began creatively asserting herself, writing more than 20 books over the years.<ref name=\":0\" /> As mentioned in an interview with Grapevine, Kalman notes how she always had a passion for writing, and that she was always interested in the field.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grape Vine- Maira Kalman |url=https://www.fromthegrapevine.com/arts/maira-kalman-new-yorker-artist}}</ref> Kalman did not consider herself just a writer, but addressed that she was a storyteller, a journalist, a designer and a humorist.\n\nOver the course of her career, Kalman has written a series of children's books about Max Stravinsky, the poet-dog.<ref>{{cite web |title=Max series |url=https://www.librarything.com/series/Max+Stravinsky}}</ref> She created the sets for the [[Mark Morris (choreographer)|Mark Morris Dance Group]] production of ''[[Four Saints in Three Acts]]'', an opera by [[Virgil Thomson|Virgil Thompson]] and [[Gertrude Stein]]. In addition, she has been a contributor for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' since 1995 and has produced many cover illustrations as well as illustrated columns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/new-yorker/|title=New Yorker|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Most notably, Kalman collaborated with [[Rick Meyerowitz]] for ''The New Yorker'' cover called New Yorkistan. This cover created a lot of attention to the public since the magazine tackled [[tribalism]] in the city. The magazine emptied the newsstands within two days.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Yorkistan |url=https://www.rickmeyerowitz.com/rick-maira/new-yorkistan/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Kalman's children's book, ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of John J. Harvey'', was released. This focuses on New York City's more recent terror attack on the twin towers. [[September 11, 2001]], marks the day in which the twin towers fell. [[John J. Harvey]] served for the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] attack, being one of the first responding boats arriving to the attacks that day. This book educates many young individuals who may not have been around at the time.<ref>{{cite web |title=How I Teach my Son About 9/11 |url=https://thefederalist.com/2018/09/10/im-new-yorker-heres-teach-son-9-11/}}</ref> This book actively describes the history behind Harvey and the importance of this day.<ref>{{cite web |title=John J. Harvey Fireboat |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/books/children-s-books-982016.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Kalman is also known for her illustrations for the 2005 edition of ''[[The Elements of Style]]'', the popular guide to writing style, by [[William Strunk Jr.|William Strunk]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/arts/design/maira-kalmans-irreverent-pictures-for-the-grammar-bible.html|title=Maira Kalman's Irreverent Pictures for the Grammar Bible|last=Smith|first=Roberta|date=2017-08-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She also designed production sets for an opera about Gertrude Stein.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalmans Playful Book Illustrations |url=https://www.ajc.com/events/high-museum-show-spotlights-maira-kalman-playful-book-illustrations/66N9URYEw2ZbRe6aVyl85K/}}</ref>\n\nKalman wrote the monthly illustrated blog, ''The Principles of Uncertainty'', for the ''[[New York Times]]'' for one year, ending in April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Principles of Uncertainty |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/opinion/1194817101063/the-principles-of-maira-kalman.html?searchResultPosition=1}}</ref> The blog was published in a book of the same title, which was released in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Principles of Uncertainty Book |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/the-principles-of-uncertainty/#1}}</ref> During 2009, Kalman wrote another illustrated blog in the ''[New York Times'' called ''And the Pursuit of Happiness''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pursuit of Happiness |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/and-the-pursuit-of-happiness/#1}}</ref> about American democracy. The blog was published as a book in 2010. The first chapter chronicles her visit to [[Washington, D.C.]] for President [[Barack Obama]]'s inauguration. Kalman's work is also featured on [[Rosenbach Museum & Library|Rosenbach Museum and Library]]'s 21st Century Abe project.\n\nKalman crafted the illustrations for author [[Daniel Handler]]'s (a.k.a. Lemony Snicket) ''[[13 Words]]'' in 2010 and ''[[Why We Broke Up]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/13words0000snic |title=13 Words |isbn=9780061664656 |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2010 |url-access=registration }}</ref> The two went on to collaborate on a series of illustrated books published by [[Museum of Modern Art|The Museum of Modern Art]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing on a Lawn |url=https://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2014/03/20/standing-on-a-lawn-with-maira-kalman/}}</ref> Exploring MoMA's collection of photography, Kalman and Handler composed three themed volumes that combined vintage photographs with Kalman's paintings and Handler's prose. \n\nIn 2014, My Favorite Things, by Maira Kalman, was published by [[Harper Design]], a division of [[HarperCollins]]. The book focused on significant objects from the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|Cooper Hewitt]] and the personal collection of Kalman, such as a pocket watch possessed by [[Abraham Lincoln]], original editions of ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Winnie-the-Pooh (book)|Winnie-the-Pooh]]'', and photographs that Kalman had taken.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/favorite-things/|title=My Favorite Things|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, she was awarded the [[List of AIGA medalists|AIGA Medal]] for her work in \"storytelling, illustration, and design while pushing the limits of all three.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the summer of 2017, Kalman collaborated with choreographer John Heginbotham to produce a theatrical and dance interpretation of Kalman's blog, ''The Principles of Uncertainty''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wfae.org/post/illustrator-maira-kaufman-moving-stage-choreographer-john-heginbotham|title=Illustrator Maira Kaufman Moving To The Stage With Choreographer John Heginbotham|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en}}</ref> It debuted in late August at Jacob's Pillow, and had its New York premier at the Brooklyn Academy of Music Fisher in late September. Kalman performed in the piece, playing herself.<ref name=\":1\" /> Then in the Fall of that year, Kalman was a resident at the [[American Academy in Rome]].<ref name=About>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/about/|title=About|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\nKalman is represented by the Julie Saul Gallery in New York City.<ref name=\":1\" /> Since 2003, Kalman has had eight exhibitions here.<ref name=About/>\n\nIn November 2019, Kalman's publications were exhibited in Amherst, Massachusetts at The Eric Carle Museum of Picture Book Art until April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Carle Museum {{!}} |url=https://www.carlemuseum.org |website=www.carlemuseum.org}}</ref> This exhibit captured Kalman's career for others to learn about her work through an educational experience.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMaira Kalman married designer [[Tibor Kalman]] in 1981. Over the course of their marriage, Maira and Tibor had two children, Lulu and Alexander. They were married eighteen years until Tibor's death from [[Non-Hodgkin lymphoma|non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]] in 1999.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKalman's mom, Sara Berman was the early source to her inspiration behind story telling and book reading. As a mother daughter activity, Kalman and her mom would go to the library and connect themselves to the characters of the books they would read.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalman and her Mom |url=https://www.ajc.com/events/high-museum-show-spotlights-maira-kalman-playful-book-illustrations/66N9URYEw2ZbRe6aVyl85K/}}</ref> In 2017, Kalman and her son Alexander got together with coordinators of [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]], The MET, and created an exhibit dedicated to Kalman's mom called \"Sara Berman's Closet.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Inside Sara Berman's Closet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/03/arts/design/inside-sara-bermans-closet-at-the-met-museum.html}}</ref> Sara Berman's Closet also became a memoir book that Kalman and her son worked on in dedication to their loved family member.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sara Berman's Closet |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/sara-bermans-closet/#1}}</ref>\n\nKalman has worked on one short film with her son titled \"The Most Wonderful Day\" which was published on [[YouTube]]. The short film is quirky and fun, opening with a scene at the kitchen table where then the film goes through vignette scenes throughout the house.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHcL9aGoV7Y</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kalman has also performed in a production of ''[[Peter & the Wolf]]'' directed by Isaac Mizrahi's at the Guggenheim's Peter B. Lewis Theater in New York City. Kalman's character is the duck which represents the sound of an oboe instrument.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Something Essential\" Q&A with Maira Kalman |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman}}</ref>\n\nShe is in a relationship with [[Rick Meyerowitz]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nKalman lives in [[Greenwich Village]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Singular Magic of Maira Kalman |url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/04/profile-maira-kalman-author-and-illustrator.html}}</ref> She has an apartment in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/the-pursuits-of-maira-kalman/|title=The Pursuits of Maira Kalman|last=Herschthal|first=Eric|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n'''Source:'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mairakalman.com/about/|title=About {{!}} Maira Kalman|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n* 2003 \u2013 Just Looking, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2003/just-looking/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2003 - Just Looking|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 I Can't Stand All the Excitement, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2005/i-can-t-stand-all-the-excitement/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2005 - I Can't Stand All The Excitement|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2007 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2007/the-principles-of-uncertainty/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2007 - The Principles of Uncertainty|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2008 \u2013 Just Looking, Beihang University, Beijing, China\n* 2009 \u2013 The Elements of Style, Memorial Art Gallery, University of Rochester, Rochester, NY\n* 2009 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, [[Jackson Fine Art]] Gallery, Atlanta, GA\n* 2009 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, Jackson Fine Art Gallery, Atlanta, GA\n* 2010 \u2013 [[Contemporary Jewish Museum]], San Francisco, CA; [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia|Institute of Contemporary Art]], University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, PA\n* 2010 \u2013 Further Illuminations, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2010/further-illuminations-recent-paintings/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - Further Illuminations: Recent Paintings - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World), [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]], New York, NY;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/maira-kalman-various-illuminations-of-a-crazy-world|title=Maira Kalman: Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World)|website=The Jewish Museum|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> [[Skirball Cultural Center]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2011 \u2013 25 Years/25 Artists, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2011 \u2013 Storied City: New York in Picture Book Art, [[Katonah Museum of Art]], Katonah, NY\n* 2012 \u2013 37 Paintings, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2012/paintings/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2012 - 37 Paintings|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 What Pete Ate from A to Z, [[Madison Children's Museum]], Madison, WI\n* 2014 \u2013 Girls Standing on Lawns and Other Projects, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/highlight/maira-kalman/show:biography|title=Julie Saul Projects - Maira Kalman - Maira Kalman|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Maira Kalman: My Favorite Things, [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|The Cooper Hewitt National Design Museum]], New York, NY<ref name=About/>\n* 2014 \u2013 The Elements of Style, [[Frist Art Museum|The Frist Center for the Visual Arts]], Nashville, TN\n* 2014 \u2013 Thomas Jefferson Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Everything, [[Monticello]], Charlottesville, VA\n* 2015 \u2013 Sara Berman's Closet, [[Mmuseumm]], New York City, NY<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/arts/design/mmuseumm-2-to-open-in-tribeca-all-20-square-feet-of-it.html|title=Mmuseumm 2 to Open in TriBeCa, All 20 Square Feet of It|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=2015-05-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Sara Berman's Closet, in collaboration with Alex Kalman, [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/exhibitions/listings/2017/sara-berman-closet|title=Sara Berman&apos;s Closet|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>\n* 2019 \u2013 The Pursuit of Everything: Maira Kalman's Books for Children, [[High Museum of Art|The High Museum of Art]], Atlanta, GA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://high.org/exhibition/the-pursuit-of-everything-maira-kalmans-books-for-children/|title=The Pursuit of Everything: Maira Kalman's Books for Children|website=High Museum of Art|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Source:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/swami-rye |title=Reviewed by Bruce Hale in New York Journal of Books |date=2018-10-09 |accessdate=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n* ''Hey Willie, See the Pyramids'' (1988) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-050840-6}}\n* ''Sayonara, Mrs. Kackleman'' (1989) Viking Kestrel/Penguin {{ISBN|0-670-82945-5}}\n* ''Max Makes a Million'' (1990) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-83545-4}}\n* ''Roarr, Calder's Circus'' (1991) Delacorte Press/Bantam Dell/Random House {{ISBN|978-0-385-30916-5}}\n* ''Max In Hollywood, Baby'' (1992) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-84479-1}}\n* ''Chicken Soup, Boots'' (1993) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-85201-7}}\n* ''Ooh-la-la, Max in Love'' (1994) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-055537-0}}\n* ''Swami on Rye: Max in India'' (1995) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-85646-6}}\n* ''Max Deluxe'' (1996) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-86837-7}}\n* ''Next Stop Grand Central'' (1999) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-399-22926-8}}\n* ''(un)Fashion'' (with her husband Tibor Kalman) (2005) Harry N. Abrams {{ISBN|978-0-8109-9229-0}}\n* ''What Pete Ate From A to Z'' (2001) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-250159-7}}\n* ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of the John J. Harvey'' (2002) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-399-23953-3}}\n* Colors: Tibor Kalman, Issues 1\u201313 (with her husband Tibor Kalman) (2002) {{ISBN|0-8109-0414-4}}\n* ''Smartypants (Pete In School)'' {{ISBN|0-399-23478-0}}\n* ''The Illustrated Elements of Style'' (with William Strunk, Jr. and E. B. White) (2008) Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-311272-3}}\n* ''The Principles of Uncertainty'' (2009) Penguin Press {{ISBN|978-1-59420-134-9}}\n* ''Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World)'' (2010) DelMonico Prestel M\u00fcnchen 2010 {{ISBN|978-3-7913-5035-6}}\n* ''13 words'' (2010) by [[Lemony Snicket]] HarperCollins Children's Books {{ISBN|9780061664656}}\n* ''And the Pursuit of Happiness'' (2010) Penguin Press {{ISBN|978-1594202674}}\n* ''Food Rules'' (2011) by [[Michael Pollan]] Penguin Group {{ISBN|9781594203084}}\n* ''Looking at Lincoln'' (2012) Nancy Paulsen Books, a division of Penguin Young Readers Group {{ISBN|9780147517982}}\n* ''Girls Standing on Lawns'' (2014) by [[Daniel Handler]] Abrams Books for Young Readers {{ISBN|978-0-870-70908-1}}\n* ''My Favorite Things'' (2014) with the Cooper-Hewitt Museum, Harper Design, an imprint of HarperCollins Publishers {{ISBN|9780062122971}}\n* ''Thomas Jefferson : Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Everything'' (2014) Nancy Paulsen Books, an imprint of Penguin Group {{ISBN|978-0-399-24040-9}}\n* ''Beloved Dog'' (2015) Penguin Press {{ISBN|9781594205941}}\n* ''Hurry Up and Wait'' (2015) by [[Daniel Handler]] Museum of Modern Art, New York {{ISBN|978-0870709593}}\n*''Weather, Weather'' (2016) by [[Daniel Handler]] Museum of Modern Art, New York {{ISBN|978-1633450141}}\n*''Cake'' (with Barbara Scott-Goodman) (2018) Penguin Press {{ISBN|9781101981542}}\n*''Swami on Rye: Max in India'' NYR Children's Collection, 2018 \n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.mairakalman.com/}}\n* {{TED speaker}}\n** [http://www.ted.com/talks/maira_kalman_the_illustrated_woman \"The illustrated woman\" (TED2007)]\n* [http://www.nypl.org/research/chss/pep/pepdesc.cfm?id=3428 Maira Kalman in conversation] with [[Paul Holdengraber]] at LIVE from the [[New York Public Library]] October 23, 2007\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110813153407/http://www.thejewishmuseum.org/kalmangallery Maira Kalman's Image Gallery]\n* [http://www.theparisreview.org/blog/2011/05/16/maira-kalman/ Studio Visit: Maira Kalman], ''[[The Paris Review]]''\n* [http://www.vanderbilt.edu/english/nashvillereview/archives/1305 Interview with Maira Kalman] in ''[[Nashville Review]]''\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071212083136/http://www.saulgallery.com/kalman/biography.html Ms. Kalman's biography]\n* {{cite journal |url=http://www.eyemagazine.com/feature.php?id=85&fid=456 |title=Maira Kalman, the surviving spirit of M&Co |first=Steven |last=Heller |journal=[[Eye (magazine)|Eye]] |publisher=Quantum Publishing |volume=12 |issue=47 |date=Spring 2003 |accessdate=2010-01-03 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100924040206/http://eyemagazine.com/feature.php?id=85&fid=456 |archive-date=2010-09-24 |url-status=dead }}\n* [http://joannarieke.wordpress.com/2010/10/12/book-coverage-maira-kalman/ ''Ahora'': Interview with Maira Kalman]\n* [http://www.thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/mkalman \"Maira Kalman: Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World)\" Exhibition (2011)] at the [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|Jewish Museum]], New York\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Kalman, Maira}}\n[[Category:1949 births]]\n[[Category:American children's book illustrators]]\n[[Category:American children's writers]]\n[[Category:American graphic designers]]\n[[Category:American people of Israeli descent]]\n[[Category:The High School of Music & Art alumni]]\n[[Category:Israeli children's writers]]\n[[Category:Israeli emigrants to the United States]]\n[[Category:Israeli graphic designers]]\n[[Category:Israeli illustrators]]\n[[Category:Israeli Jews]]\n[[Category:Jewish artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish women artists]]\n[[Category:Jewish American artists]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:The New Yorker people]]\n[[Category:People from Tel Aviv]]\n[[Category:Women graphic designers]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name = Maira Kalman\n| image = Maira kalman 2010.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = Kalman at the 2010 [[Texas Book Festival]]\n| birth_name = <!--if different-->\n| birth_date = {{Birth year and age|1949}}\n| birth_place = [[Tel Aviv]], [[Israel]]\n| nationality = American\n| known_for = [[Illustrator]], [[writer]]\n| education = New York University\n| movement = \n| spouse = Tibor Kalman (m. 1981, d. 1999)\n| notable_works = \n| patrons = \n| awards = \n| website = {{URL | mairakalman.com | MairaKalman.com }}\n}}\n\n'''Maira Kalman''' ({{lang-he|\u05de\u05d0\u05d9\u05e8\u05d4 \u05e7\u05dc\u05de\u05df}}; born 1949) is an [[Israel]]i-born American illustrator, writer, artist, and designer. She is known for her playful and witty illustrations, featured in publications such as ''[[The New York Times]]'' and ''[[The New Yorker]]'', and the children's books that she has both written and illustrated.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fromthegrapevine.com/arts/maira-kalman-new-yorker-artist|title=Maira Kalman is more than just a quirky cartoonist for The New Yorker|website=From the Grapevine|language=en|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/04/profile-maira-kalman-author-and-illustrator.html|title=The Singular Magic of Maira Kalman|last=Alam|first=Rumaan|date=2018-04-30|website=The Cut|language=en-us|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> The urban environment of [[New York City]] brings Kalman's creativity to life. She has collaborated with New York institutions, such as [[The Museum of Modern Art]]. She has also drawn inspiration from the city's geography and well known landmarks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman|title=\"Something Essential\": A Q&A with Maira Kalman|date=2014-07-01|website=Guggenheim|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Her [[picture book]], ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of the John J. Harvey'', can be found in [[WorldCat]] library. This book was both written and illustrated by Kalman. It won the annual [[Boston Globe\u2013Horn Book Award]] for Nonfiction in 2003.<ref>[https://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n86-012344/ \"Kalman, Maira\"]. [[WorldCat]]. Retrieved 2014-10-02.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nKalman was born in [[Tel Aviv]], Israel. Her parents had emigrated to Israel in the 1930s, and her father was a fervent [[Zionism|Zionist]] who was a member of [[Irgun]].<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/the-pursuits-of-maira-kalman/|title=The Pursuits of Maira Kalman|last=Herschthal|first=Eric|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> Her mother, Sara Berman, was originally from [[Belarus]] and had moved to Israel to escape [[Pogrom|pogroms]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Green|first=Penelope|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/03/arts/design/inside-sara-bermans-closet-at-the-met-museum.html|title=Inside Sara Berman's Closet at the Met Museum|date=2017-03-03|work=The New York Times|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> When Kalman was growing up in Israel, the women in her family \"...worked like beasts from morning to night. It was that sense of dedicating yourself to a life of taking care of the people you love, by baking and sewing and cleaning,\" Kalman explained.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nWhen Kalman was four years old, her family moved to [[New York City]], so that her father could expand his diamond business.<ref>{{cite web |title=Julie Saul Projects |url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/highlight/maira-kalman/the-autobiography-of-alice-b-toklas}}</ref><ref name=\":4\" /> The family lived in [[Riverdale, Bronx]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman|title=\"Something Essential\": A Q&A with Maira Kalman|date=2014-07-01|website=Guggenheim|language=en-US|access-date=2019-12-06}}</ref> Her mother, Sara, spent a significant amount of time at the [[Loehmann's]] department store.<ref name=\":5\" /> She was known for her chic style, and she wore only white. Kalman attended the [[High School of Music & Art]], now known as [[Fiorello H. LaGuardia High School|LaGuardia High School]], where she studied art and received a Bachelors of Arts degree.<ref>[http://illustrationfriday.com/blog/2008/09/28/master-of-the-month-maira-kalman/ Master of the Month: Maira Kalman] from ''IllustrationFriday.com''</ref> She attended [[New York University]] where she studied English literature.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.saulgallery.com/kalman/biography.html|title=Julie Saul Gallery|date=2007-12-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071212083136/http://www.saulgallery.com/kalman/biography.html|access-date=2019-04-02|archive-date=December 12, 2007}}</ref> By the time Kalman had left for college, her parents had returned to Israel.<ref name=\":4\" />\n\nAt the age of 18, Kalman met designer [[Tibor Kalman]], a native of [[Budapest]] who had moved to New York City as a child, at New York University.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=https://collection.cooperhewitt.org/people/18048717/|title=M&Co {{!}} People {{!}} Collection of Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|website=collection.cooperhewitt.org|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> She explained, \"We met in this class of misfits in summer school. They said, {{em|You have to take these classes, otherwise we're going to throw you out.}} What was interesting was the mix of crazy people in that group... So we met there, and he asked me out on a date. And you know in your life, when you meet somebody [and] you go, 'I've known you for a thousand years,' and there's not even an iota of a question?\"<ref name=\":2\" />\n\n== Career ==\nIn 1979, Maira and Tibor founded the graphic and design consultancy, [[M & Co. (design firm)|M & Co.]] The firm grew to be highly influential; it was known for its innovative use of images and typography.<ref name=\":3\" /> M & Co. created work for ''[[Interview (magazine)|Interview]]'' magazine, Restaurant Florent, the band [[Talking Heads]], the [[National Audubon Society]], and the [[Museum of Modern Art]].<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.aiga.org/aiga/content/inspiration/aiga-medalist/2016-aiga-medalist-maira-kalman/|title=2016 AIGA Medalist Maira Kalman|work=AIGA {{!}} the professional association for design|access-date=2017-04-13}}</ref><ref name=\":3\" /> \n\nKalman played a critical role in the development of M & Co, but her priorities began to shift with the birth of her children, Lulu (1983) and Alex (1985).<ref name=\":2\" /> Beginning in the mid-1980s, Kalman began to publish children's book. Her first children's book, ''Stay Up Late'' (1985), featured illustrations paired lyrics of musician [[David Byrne]]. The book told the story of children who prevent their baby brother from falling asleep.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.publishersweekly.com/978-0-670-81895-2|title=Stay Up Late|website=www.publishersweekly.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\nIn 1990s, Tibor served as the [[editor-in-chief]] of [[Colors (magazine)|''COLORS'' magazine]]. The magazine was known for confronting topics such as [[ecology]] and [[HIV/AIDS]].<ref>{{Cite news|last=Porter|first=By Mark|url=https://www.theguardian.com/news/1999/may/07/guardianobituaries.markporter|title=Tibor Kalman|date=1999-05-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2020-03-08|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 1999, Tibor passed away. Maira Kalman began creatively asserting herself, writing more than 20 books over the years.<ref name=\":0\" /> As mentioned in an interview with Grapevine, Kalman notes how she always had a passion for writing, and that she was always interested in the field.<ref>{{cite web |title=Grape Vine- Maira Kalman |url=https://www.fromthegrapevine.com/arts/maira-kalman-new-yorker-artist}}</ref> Kalman did not consider herself just a writer, but addressed that she was a storyteller, a journalist, a designer and a humorist.\n\nOver the course of her career, Kalman has written a series of children's books about Max Stravinsky, the poet-dog.<ref>{{cite web |title=Max series |url=https://www.librarything.com/series/Max+Stravinsky}}</ref> She created the sets for the [[Mark Morris (choreographer)|Mark Morris Dance Group]] production of ''[[Four Saints in Three Acts]]'', an opera by [[Virgil Thomson|Virgil Thompson]] and [[Gertrude Stein]]. In addition, she has been a contributor for ''[[The New Yorker]]'' since 1995 and has produced many cover illustrations as well as illustrated columns.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/new-yorker/|title=New Yorker|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref> Most notably, Kalman collaborated with [[Rick Meyerowitz]] for''The New Yorker'' cover called New Yorkistan. This cover created a lot of attention to the public since the magazine tackled [[tribalism]] in the city. The magazine emptied the newsstands within two days.<ref>{{cite web |title=New Yorkistan |url=https://www.rickmeyerowitz.com/rick-maira/new-yorkistan/}}</ref>\n\nIn 2002, Kalman's children's book, ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of John J. Harvey'', was released. This focuses on New York City's more recent terror attack on the twin towers. [[September 11, 2001]], marks the day in which the twin towers fell. [[John J. Harvey]] served for the [[World Trade Center (1973\u20132001)|World Trade Center]] attack, being one of the first responding boats arriving to the attacks that day. This book educates many young individuals who may not have been around at the time.<ref>{{cite web |title=How I Teach my Son About 9/11 |url=https://thefederalist.com/2018/09/10/im-new-yorker-heres-teach-son-9-11/}}</ref> This book actively describes the history behind Harvey and the importance of this day.<ref>{{cite web |title=John J. Harvey Fireboat |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2002/09/29/books/children-s-books-982016.html}}</ref>\n\nIn 2005, Kalman is also known for her illustrations for the 2005 edition of ''[[The Elements of Style]]'', the popular guide to writing style, by [[William Strunk Jr.|William Strunk]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/17/arts/design/maira-kalmans-irreverent-pictures-for-the-grammar-bible.html|title=Maira Kalman's Irreverent Pictures for the Grammar Bible|last=Smith|first=Roberta|date=2017-08-17|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref> She also designed production sets for an opera about Gertrude Stein.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalmans Playful Book Illustrations |url=https://www.ajc.com/events/high-museum-show-spotlights-maira-kalman-playful-book-illustrations/66N9URYEw2ZbRe6aVyl85K/}}</ref>\n\nKalman wrote the monthly illustrated blog, ''The Principles of Uncertainty'', for the ''[[New York Times]]'' for one year, ending in April 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Principles of Uncertainty |url=https://www.nytimes.com/video/opinion/1194817101063/the-principles-of-maira-kalman.html?searchResultPosition=1}}</ref> The blog was published in a book of the same title, which was released in 2007.<ref>{{cite web |title=Principles of Uncertainty Book |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/the-principles-of-uncertainty/#1}}</ref> During 2009, Kalman wrote another illustrated blog in the ''[New York Times'' called ''And the Pursuit of Happiness''<ref>{{cite web |title=Pursuit of Happiness |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/and-the-pursuit-of-happiness/#1}}</ref> about American democracy. The blog was published as a book in 2010. The first chapter chronicles her visit to [[Washington, D.C.]] for President [[Barack Obama]]'s inauguration. Kalman's work is also featured on [[Rosenbach Museum & Library|Rosenbach Museum and Library]]'s 21st Century Abe project.\n\nKalman crafted the illustrations for author [[Daniel Handler]]'s (a.k.a. Lemony Snicket) ''[[13 Words]]'' in 2010 and ''[[Why We Broke Up]]'' in 2011.<ref>{{cite book |url=https://archive.org/details/13words0000snic |title=13 Words |isbn=9780061664656 |publisher=[[HarperCollins]] |year=2010 |url-access=registration }}</ref> The two went on to collaborate on a series of illustrated books published by [[Museum of Modern Art|The Museum of Modern Art]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Standing on a Lawn |url=https://www.moma.org/explore/inside_out/2014/03/20/standing-on-a-lawn-with-maira-kalman/}}</ref> Exploring MoMA's collection of photography, Kalman and Handler composed three themed volumes that combined vintage photographs with Kalman's paintings and Handler's prose. \n\nIn 2014, My Favorite Things, by Maira Kalman, was published by [[Harper Design]], a division of [[HarperCollins]]. The book focused on significant objects from the [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|Cooper Hewitt]] and the personal collection of Kalman, such as a pocket watch possessed by [[Abraham Lincoln]], original editions of ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' and ''[[Winnie-the-Pooh (book)|Winnie-the-Pooh]]'', and photographs that Kalman had taken.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/favorite-things/|title=My Favorite Things|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref> \n\nIn 2017, she was awarded the [[List of AIGA medalists|AIGA Medal]] for her work in \"storytelling, illustration, and design while pushing the limits of all three.\"<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn the summer of 2017, Kalman collaborated with choreographer John Heginbotham to produce a theatrical and dance interpretation of Kalman's blog, ''The Principles of Uncertainty''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://wfae.org/post/illustrator-maira-kaufman-moving-stage-choreographer-john-heginbotham|title=Illustrator Maira Kaufman Moving To The Stage With Choreographer John Heginbotham|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en}}</ref> It debuted in late August at Jacob's Pillow, and had its New York premier at the Brooklyn Academy of Music Fisher in late September. Kalman performed in the piece, playing herself.<ref name=\":1\" /> Then in the Fall of that year, Kalman was a resident at the [[American Academy in Rome]].<ref name=About>{{Cite web|url=https://www.mairakalman.com/about/|title=About|website=Maira Kalman|access-date=2019-04-02}}</ref>\n\nKalman is represented by the Julie Saul Gallery in New York City.<ref name=\":1\" /> Since 2003, Kalman has had eight exhibitions here.<ref name=About/>\n\nIn November 2019, Kalman's publications were exhibited in Amherst, Massachusetts at The Eric Carle Museum of Picture Book Art until April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Carle Museum {{!}} |url=https://www.carlemuseum.org |website=www.carlemuseum.org}}</ref> This exhibit captured Kalman's career for others to learn about her work through an educational experience.\n\n== Personal life ==\nMaira Kalman married designer [[Tibor Kalman]] in 1981. Over the course of their marriage, Maira and Tibor had two children, Lulu and Alexander. They were married eighteen years until Tibor's death from [[Non-Hodgkin lymphoma|non-Hodgkin's lymphoma]] in 1999.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nKalman's mom, Sara Berman was the early source to her inspiration behind story telling and book reading. As a mother daughter activity, Kalman and her mom would go to the library and connect themselves to the characters of the books they would read.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kalman and her Mom |url=https://www.ajc.com/events/high-museum-show-spotlights-maira-kalman-playful-book-illustrations/66N9URYEw2ZbRe6aVyl85K/}}</ref> In 2017, Kalman and her son Alexander got together with coordinators of [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]], The MET, and created an exhibit dedicated to Kalman's mom called \"Sara Berman's Closet.\"<ref>{{cite web |title=Inside Sara Berman's Closet |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/03/03/arts/design/inside-sara-bermans-closet-at-the-met-museum.html}}</ref> Sara Berman's Closet also became a memoir book that Kalman and her son worked on in dedication to their loved family member.<ref>{{cite web |title=Sara Berman's Closet |url=https://www.mairakalman.com/books/adult/sara-bermans-closet/#1}}</ref>\n\nKalman has worked on one short film with her son titled \"The Most Wonderful Day\" which was published on [[YouTube]]. The short film is quirky and fun, opening with a scene at the kitchen table where then the film goes through vignette scenes throughout the house.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=WHcL9aGoV7Y</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Kalman has also performed in a production of ''[[Peter & the Wolf]]'' directed by Isaac Mizrahi's at the Guggenheim's Peter B. Lewis Theater in New York City. Kalman's character is the duck which represents the sound of an oboe instrument.<ref>{{cite web |title=\"Something Essential\" Q&A with Maira Kalman |url=https://www.guggenheim.org/blogs/checklist/something-essential-a-q-and-a-with-maira-kalman}}</ref>\n\nShe is in a relationship with [[Rick Meyerowitz]].<ref name=\":5\" />\n\nKalman lives in [[Greenwich Village]] in New York City.<ref>{{cite web |title=The Singular Magic of Maira Kalman |url=https://www.thecut.com/2018/04/profile-maira-kalman-author-and-illustrator.html}}</ref> She has an apartment in Tel Aviv.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jewishweek.timesofisrael.com/the-pursuits-of-maira-kalman/|title=The Pursuits of Maira Kalman|last=Herschthal|first=Eric|website=jewishweek.timesofisrael.com|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n\n== Exhibitions ==\n'''Source:'''<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.mairakalman.com/about/|title=About {{!}} Maira Kalman|language=en-US|access-date=2016-06-26}}</ref>\n\n* 2003 \u2013 Just Looking, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2003/just-looking/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2003 - Just Looking|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2005 \u2013 I Can't Stand All the Excitement, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2005/i-can-t-stand-all-the-excitement/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2005 - I Can't Stand All The Excitement|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2007 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2007/the-principles-of-uncertainty/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2007 - The Principles of Uncertainty|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2008 \u2013 Just Looking, Beihang University, Beijing, China\n* 2009 \u2013 The Elements of Style, Memorial Art Gallery, University of Rochester, Rochester, NY\n* 2009 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, [[Jackson Fine Art]] Gallery, Atlanta, GA\n* 2009 \u2013 The Principles of Uncertainty, Jackson Fine Art Gallery, Atlanta, GA\n* 2010 \u2013 [[Contemporary Jewish Museum]], San Francisco, CA; [[Institute of Contemporary Art, Philadelphia|Institute of Contemporary Art]], University of Pennsylvania, Philadelphia, PA\n* 2010 \u2013 Further Illuminations, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2010/further-illuminations-recent-paintings/images|title=Julie Saul Projects - Further Illuminations: Recent Paintings - Images|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2010 \u2013 Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World), [[Jewish Museum (Manhattan)|The Jewish Museum]], New York, NY;<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://thejewishmuseum.org/exhibitions/maira-kalman-various-illuminations-of-a-crazy-world|title=Maira Kalman: Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World)|website=The Jewish Museum|access-date=2017-04-26}}</ref> [[Skirball Cultural Center]], Los Angeles, CA\n* 2011 \u2013 25 Years/25 Artists, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY\n* 2011 \u2013 Storied City: New York in Picture Book Art, [[Katonah Museum of Art]], Katonah, NY\n* 2012 \u2013 37 Paintings, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/exhibition-history/2012/paintings/show:press|title=Julie Saul Projects - 2012 - 37 Paintings|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2013 \u2013 What Pete Ate from A to Z, [[Madison Children's Museum]], Madison, WI\n* 2014 \u2013 Girls Standing on Lawns and Other Projects, Julie Saul Gallery, New York, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://juliesaulprojects.com/highlight/maira-kalman/show:biography|title=Julie Saul Projects - Maira Kalman - Maira Kalman|website=juliesaulprojects.com|access-date=2020-03-08}}</ref>\n* 2014 \u2013 Maira Kalman: My Favorite Things, [[Cooper Hewitt, Smithsonian Design Museum|The Cooper Hewitt National Design Museum]], New York, NY<ref name=About/>\n* 2014 \u2013 The Elements of Style, [[Frist Art Museum|The Frist Center for the Visual Arts]], Nashville, TN\n* 2014 \u2013 Thomas Jefferson Life, Liberty and the Pursuit of Everything, [[Monticello]], Charlottesville, VA\n* 2015 \u2013 Sara Berman's Closet, [[Mmuseumm]], New York City, NY<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2015/05/29/arts/design/mmuseumm-2-to-open-in-tribeca-all-20-square-feet-of-it.html|title=Mmuseumm 2 to Open in TriBeCa, All 20 Square Feet of It|last=Ryzik|first=Melena|date=2015-05-28|work=The New York Times|access-date=2017-12-26|language=en-US|issn=0362-4331}}</ref>\n* 2017 \u2013 Sara Berman's Closet, in collaboration with Alex Kalman, [[The Metropolitan Museum of Art]], New York City, NY<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.metmuseum.org/exhibitions/listings/2017/sara-berman-closet|title=Sara Berman&apos;s Closet|website=The Metropolitan Museum of Art, i.e. The Met Museum|access-date=2017-12-26}}</ref>\n* 2019 \u2013 The Pursuit of Everything: Maira Kalman's Books for Children, [[High Museum of Art|The High Museum of Art]], Atlanta, GA<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://high.org/exhibition/the-pursuit-of-everything-maira-kalmans-books-for-children/|title=The Pursuit of Everything: Maira Kalman's Books for Children|website=High Museum of Art|language=en-US|access-date=2019-04-01}}</ref>\n\n== Bibliography ==\n'''Source:'''<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.nyjournalofbooks.com/book-review/swami-rye |title=Reviewed by Bruce Hale in New York Journal of Books |date=2018-10-09 |accessdate=2018-12-12}}</ref>\n\n* ''Hey Willie, See the Pyramids'' (1988) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-050840-6}}\n* ''Sayonara, Mrs. Kackleman'' (1989) Viking Kestrel/Penguin {{ISBN|0-670-82945-5}}\n* ''Max Makes a Million'' (1990) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-83545-4}}\n* ''Roarr, Calder's Circus'' (1991) Delacorte Press/Bantam Dell/Random House {{ISBN|978-0-385-30916-5}}\n* ''Max In Hollywood, Baby'' (1992) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-84479-1}}\n* ''Chicken Soup, Boots'' (1993) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-85201-7}}\n* ''Ooh-la-la, Max in Love'' (1994) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-055537-0}}\n* ''Swami on Rye: Max in India'' (1995) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-85646-6}}\n* ''Max Deluxe'' (1996) Viking/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-670-86837-7}}\n* ''Next Stop Grand Central'' (1999) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-399-22926-8}}\n* ''(un)Fashion'' (with her husband Tibor Kalman) (2005) Harry N. Abrams {{ISBN|978-0-8109-9229-0}}\n* ''What Pete Ate From A to Z'' (2001) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-250159-7}}\n* ''Fireboat: The Heroic Adventures of the John J. Harvey'' (2002) Putnam/Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-399-23953-3}}\n* Colors: Tibor Kalman, Issues 1\u201313 (with her husband Tibor Kalman) (2002) {{ISBN|0-8109-0414-4}}\n* ''Smartypants (Pete In School)'' {{ISBN|0-399-23478-0}}\n* ''The Illustrated Elements of Style'' (with William Strunk, Jr. and E. B. White) (2008) Penguin {{ISBN|978-0-14-311272-3}}\n* ''The Principles of Uncertainty'' (2009) Penguin Press {{ISBN|978-1-59420-134-9}}\n* ''Various Illuminations (of a Crazy World)'' (2010) DelMonico Prestel M\u00fcnchen 2010 {{ISBN|978-3-7913-5035-6}}\n* ''13 words'' (2010) by [[Lemony Snicket]] HarperCollins Children's Books {{ISBN|9780061664656}}\n* ''And the Pursuit of Happiness'' (2010) Penguin Press {{ISBN|978-1594202674}}\n* ''Food Rules'' (2011) by [[Michael Pollan]] Penguin Group {{ISBN|9781594203084}}\n* ''Looking at Lincoln'' (2012) Nancy Paulsen Books, a division of Penguin Young Readers Group {{ISBN|9780147517982}}\n* ''Girls Standing on Lawns'' (2014) by [[Daniel Handler]] Abrams Books for Youn